{{Vaishnavism}} 
The '''Ramanandi''' ([[IAST]] {{IAST|Rāmānandī}}), also known as the '''Ramayats''' or the '''Ramavats''' ([[IAST]] {{IAST|Rāmāvat}}),{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}} are a branch of the '''[[Vaishnava]] [[Sri Sampradaya]]''' of [[Hinduism]].{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}}

==Caste==
People of this caste are known as '''Vaishnav Brahmins''' in Gujarat, Uttar Pradesh And Rajasthan. At the beginning of the 20th century, this sect declared to be the descendants of [[Lord Rama|Rāma's]] sons, [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] and [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]].{{sfn|Jaffrelot|2003}}
This Caste People were From Different castes Of Jats and Rajputs. They Have Brahman, Jat and Rajput Gotras.
They Fought Many Wars with Mughals. After Renuciating Weapons ,they Began to do Brahman things and Started Studying Vedas and Upanishads.

==Denomination==
[[File:Unknown Indian - Rama, Lakshmana, and Sita Cooking and Eating in the Wilderness - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|[[Rama]], [[Sita]], and [[Lakshmana]] cooking and eating in the Wilderness (picture).]]
The Ramanandi Sampradaya is one of the largest and most egalitarian Hindu sects India, around the [[Ganges Plain]], and Nepal today.{{sfn| Burghart |1983|p=362}} It mainly emphasizes the worship of [[Rama|Rāma]],{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}} as well as [[Vishnu]] directly and other incarnations.{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}} While considered Vaiṣṇava, the Ramanandi are the largest ascetic group that celebrates the [[Maha Shivaratri|Śivarātri]] festival, which is dedicated to [[Shiva]].{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=255|quote=And finally, it must be noted that many groups that are considered {{IAST|Vaiṣṇava}} also worship {{IAST|Śiva}}. The largest ascetic groups that celebrate the Śivaratri festival with mortification of the flesh and pilgrimages are the {{IAST|Vaiṣṇava}} {{IAST|Rāmānandī}}s.}} {{IAST|Rāmānandī}} ascetics rely upon meditation and strict ascetic practices, but also believe that the grace of god is required for them to achieve liberation. For that reason, the {{IAST|Tyāga}} section of the {{IAST|Rāmānandī}} ascetics, unlike some {{IAST|Śaiva}} ascetics, do not cut the [[Upanayana|sacred thread]].{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=316|loc="Wear a Sacred Thread" is noted as a distinctive mark of {{IAST|Rāmānandī}} ascetics in Table 33, "Groups and Sects of Ascetics".}} Their reasoning for this is that only {{IAST|Viṣṇu}} or {{IAST|Rāma}} can grant liberation.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=256}}

Most Ramanandis consider themselves to be the followers of [[Ramananda]], a [[Vaishnava]] saint in medieval India.{{sfn|Raj|Harman|2007|p=165}} Philosophically, they are in the [[Vishishtadvaita]] ([[IAST]] {{IAST|Viśiṣṭādvaita}}) tradition.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}}

Its ascetic wing constitutes the largest Vaishnava [[Hindu monasticism|monastic order]] and may possibly be the largest monastic order in all of India.{{sfn|Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia 1999}} There are two major subgroups of Ramanandi ascetics: the Tyagi, who use ash for initiation, and the Naga, who are the militant wing.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=316}}

== History ==
{{See also|Ramananda}}

''[[Bhaktamal]]'', a gigantic hagiographic work on Hindu saints and devotees written by Raghavadas in 1660,{{sfn|Callewaert|Snell|1994|p=95}} was a core text for all Vaishnavas including Ramanandis.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=55}} This text lists [[Ramanuja]], expounder of [[Vishishtadvaita]] school of Vedanta, and Ramananda as saints of the [[Sri Sampradaya|Ramanuja Sampradaya]] but Galta peeth of Ramanandi Vaishnavas have ruled out this by prohibiting Ramanuja Vaishnavas from taking Shahi snan in [[Kumbh Mela]].{{sfn|Callewaert|Snell|1994|p=97}} Many localized commentaries of ''Bhaktakamal'' were taught to young Vaishnavas across India. In the 19th century, proliferation of the printing press in the [[Gangetic plain]]s of North India allowed various commentaries of the text to be widely distributed. Of these, Bhagavan Prasad's ''Shri Bhaktamal: Tika, Tilak, aur Namvali Sahit'' was considered to be the most authoritative.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=55}} In this text, Bhagvan Prasad lists 108 prominent Vaishnavas starting with Ramanuja and ending with Ramananda.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=56}} Ramananda's guru Raghavananda is described as an egalitarian guru who taught students of all castes. Ramananda himself is described as an [[avatar]] of [[Rama]], a humble student with great yogic talents who was asked to form his own sampradaya as a punishment by his guru.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|pp=57–58}} The text located his birth in [[Prayag]] in c. 1300 CE.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=57}}

[[J.N. Farquhar]], a noted missionary and indologist, published his own work on the Ramanandi Sampradaya based on his interaction with various Ramanandis at the ''[[Kumbh Mela]]'' of 1918.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=60}} Farquhar credits Ramananda (c. 1400–1470 CE){{sfn|Farquhar|1920|p=323}} and his followers as the origin of the North Indian practice of using Ram to refer to the [[Absolute (philosophy)|Absolute]].{{sfn|Farquhar|1920|pp=323–324}} Based on the textual evidence and similarity of sect marks between Ramanandis and Sri Vaishnavas, Farquhar concludes that Ramananda migrated to [[Benares]] from [[Tamil Nadu]]. He acknowledges that Ramananda accepted disciples from all castes and did not observe the restrictions in matters of food. However, Farquhar finds no evidence to show that Ramananda endeavoured to "overturn caste as a social institution".{{sfn|Farquhar|1920|pp=324–325}} On the other hand, Sita Ram, author of the ''Vaishnava history of Ayodhya'', and [[George Abraham Grierson|George Grierson]], eminent linguist and Indologist, represent Ramananda as saint who tried to transcend caste divisions of medieval India through the message of love and equality. The scholars also disagree on Ramananda's connection with Ramanuja. While Farquhar finds them completely unconnected, Sita Ram and Grierson place Ramananda within the Ramanuja tradition.{{sfn|Pinch|1996|p=61}}

Up to the nineteenth century, many of the trade routes in northern India were guarded by groups of warrior-ascetics, including the Nāgā sections of the Rāmānandīs, who were feared because of their strength and fearlessness.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=274}} The British took steps to disarm these militant groups of ascetics, but even today the sects still retain their heroic traditions.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=274}}

==Geography==
Ramanandi live chiefly in the northern part of India.{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}} Ramanandi monasteries are found throughout western and central India, the Ganges basin, the Nepalese [[Terai]], and the Himalayan foothills.{{sfn| Burghart |1983|p=362}} Ramanandis are spread across [[India]], mainly in [[Gujarat]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]]. The majority of Hindu immigrants to [[Trinidad and Tobago]] belonged to Vaishnava sects such as the Ramanandi. Hindus in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] currently practice based on the teachings of Ramananda.{{sfn|West|2001|p=743}}

==Saints==
Saints [[Dhanna Bhagat|Dhanna]] and [[Bhagat Pipa|Pipa]] were among the immediate disciples of Ramananda.{{sfn|Farquhar|1920|p=328}} Hymns written by them find mention in the [[Adi Granth]], holy scripture of the [[Sikhs]].{{sfn|Schomer|McLeod|1987|p=5}} Sects founded by saints [[Raidas]], Sena and Maluk Das are also of a direct Ramanandi origin.{{sfn|Farquhar|1920|p=328}}

The poet-saint [[Tulsidas]], who composed the [[Ramcharitmanas]], was a member of this sect.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}}{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}} His writings made [[Vishnu]] and [[Shiva]] devotees of each other and thereby bridged the gap between Vaishnavas and Shaivites. Because Tulsidas attempted to reconcile various theologies scholars like [[Ramchandra Shukla]] do not agree that he can considered to be a Ramanandi exclusively.{{sfn|Shukla|2002|p=44}}

Some sources say [[Jayadeva]], who composed the [[Gita Govinda]], was also a member of this sect.{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}} Other sources classify Jayadeva simply as a Bengal Vaishnava.{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}}

Some sources say that [[Kabir]] was a disciple of Ramananda.{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}} Other sources say that [[Ramananda]] was a student of [[Kabir]].{{sfn|Michaels|2004|p=254}} Kabir also founded a separate sect that is now known as the [[Kabirpanthi]].{{sfn|Tattwananda|1984|p=10}}

